  "text": "## Dashboard JSON Schema Version Migration Pipeline\n\nThe Grafana dashboard migration system implements a comprehensive two-tier pipeline with parallel implementations in both Go (backend) and TypeScript (frontend) to ensure consistent schema versioning and dashboard transformation across the application.\n\n### Backend Migration Infrastructure (Go)\n\n**Migration Runner** (`apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/migrate.go`):\n- Provides the `Migrate()` function which is the main entry point for migrating dashboards\n- Uses a singleton `migrator` struct that manages the migration pipeline\n- `Initialize()` function sets up the migrator with data source information\n- Orchestrates the full migration pipeline including frontend defaults application, panel ID management, schema version migrations, and cleanup operations\n- The migration flow: cleanup → apply defaults → migrate versions → add annotations → cleanup for save\n\n**Migration Registry** (`apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/migrations.go`):\n- `GetMigrations()` function returns a map[int]SchemaVersionMigrationFunc mapping version numbers to migration functions\n- Maps versions 2-42 to individual migration functions (V2 through V42)\n- Some migrations like V33 and V36 use closures to capture DataSourceInfoProvider for dynamic datasource lookups\n- Latest version is 42 (marked as final for v1 dashboard API)\n- `SchemaVersionMigrationFunc` type defines the signature for all migration functions: `func(context.Context, map[string]interface{}) error`\n\n**Individual Migration Steps**:\n- V2 (`v2.go`): Migrates legacy services.filter structure to time and templating properties\n- V16 (`v16.go`): Migrates dashboard layout from row-based system to modern grid-based layout\n- V36 (`v36.go`): Converts datasource references from string format to structured UID-based objects\n- V37-V42: Various panel and dashboard refinements\n- V3-V15, V17-V35, V38-V41: Additional schema refinements and normalizations\n\n**Frontend Defaults Application** (`apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/frontend_defaults.go`):\n- `applyFrontendDefaults()`: Applies DashboardModel constructor defaults (title, tags, timezone, time range, etc.)\n- `applyPanelDefaults()`: Applies PanelModel defaults to all panels (gridPos, targets with refId:A, fieldConfig, etc.)\n- `cleanupDashboardForSave()`: Removes non-persisted properties and null values to match frontend's getSaveModel behavior\n- `applyPanelAutoMigration()`: Handles auto-migration of legacy panel types (graph→timeseries, table-old→table, singlestat→stat, etc.)\n- Manages panel ID uniqueness and grid position sorting\n\n**Utilities and Error Handling**:\n- `migration_utils.go`: Provides helper functions for safe type conversions (GetStringValue, GetBoolValue, GetIntValue, GetFloatValue, ConvertToFloat, ConvertToInt)\n- `errors.go`: Defines MigrationError and MinimumVersionError types for detailed error reporting\n- `datasource_utils.go`: Provides datasource reference conversion utilities\n\n### Frontend Migration Implementation (TypeScript)\n\n**DashboardMigrator** (`public/app/features/dashboard/state/DashboardMigrator.ts`):\n- `DashboardMigrator` class with `updateSchema()` method that mirrors the backend migration logic\n- `DASHBOARD_SCHEMA_VERSION = 42` constant marking the final version (no new schema versions are added)\n- Implements schema version migrations for v2-v42 with conditional blocks checking oldVersion < targetVersion\n- Handles panel type migrations, datasource reference conversions, and field config transformations\n- Imports specialized migration functions for CloudWatch metrics and annotations\n\n**DashboardModel** (`public/app/features/dashboard/state/DashboardModel.ts`):\n- Main dashboard model class that instantiates DashboardMigrator\n- Manages schemaVersion property and handles default values\n- Integrates with PanelModel for panel-level migrations\n- Supports targetSchemaVersion parameter for single-version migrations\n\n**PanelModel** (`public/app/features/dashboard/state/PanelModel.ts`):\n- Panel-level model with auto-migration logic for legacy panel types\n- Handles panel plugin type mapping and field config management\n- Works in conjunction with getPanelPluginToMigrateTo for determining target panel types\n\n**Panel Type Migration** (`public/app/features/dashboard/state/getPanelPluginToMigrateTo.ts`):\n- `getPanelPluginToMigrateTo()` function determines which panel plugin type legacy panels should migrate to\n- Handles graph panel special logic (migrates to timeseries by default, bargauge or barchart based on xaxis mode, histogram for histogram mode)\n- Maps deprecated panel types: table-old→table, singlestat→stat, grafana-singlestat-panel→stat, grafana-piechart-panel→piechart, grafana-worldmap-panel→geomap, natel-discrete-panel→state-timeline\n\n### Testing Infrastructure\n\n**Test Files**:\n- Individual version test files (`v2_test.go` through `v42_test.go`) verify each migration step\n- `DashboardMigrator.test.ts`: Frontend migration tests validating the TypeScript implementation\n- `DashboardMigratorToBackend.test.ts`: Comprehensive comparison tests ensuring backend and frontend migration produce identical results\n- Test data includes 40+ curated dashboard JSON files covering various schema versions and scenarios\n\n**Documentation**:\n- `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/README.md`: Comprehensive guide covering:\n  - Migration architecture and design patterns\n  - How to add new migrations (now discouraged - new panel migrations should be done at plugin level)\n  - Frontend and backend implementation details\n  - Testing strategies including single-version and full-pipeline tests\n  - Dataset coverage spanning v14-v42\n\n### Architecture Highlights\n\n1. **Parallel Implementation**: Both backend (Go) and frontend (TypeScript) implement the exact same logic to ensure consistency\n2. **Stateless Migrations**: Each migration step is a pure function operating on the dashboard object\n3. **Version Sequencing**: Migrations are applied sequentially from current version to target version\n4. **Schema Versioning**: Version 42 is final - no new schema versions are added; panel-specific migrations are handled by panel plugins\n5. **Datasource Handling**: V33 and V36 migrations require datasource information, using DataSourceInfoProvider interface\n6. **Default Values Management**: Frontend defaults are applied before migrations to ensure consistent behavior\n7. **Cleanup Phase**: Post-migration cleanup removes non-persisted properties and null values to match save model behavior\n\nThe system successfully bridges frontend and backend implementations, ensuring that dashboards can be reliably migrated through 40+ schema versions while maintaining consistency and data integrity across the Grafana ecosystem."
